","about 1310":"about 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thirkell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name; according to   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  , the modern Yorks and Durham name is probably not from the name in (2) but a metathesized variant of   Threlkeld  . The connection is unambiguous in Lancelot Threlkelde, 1472 in   Yorks Deeds   (Londesborough, ER Yorks), and Christopher Thirkylde, 1556, Elizabeth Therkall, 1608 in   York Registry Wills   (Goodmanham, ER Yorks). Later examples include Thomas Thirkell, 1624, Thomasine Threlkeld, 1673 in   IGI   (Brancepeth, Durham); John Thirkeld, 1741, Dorothy Threlkeld, 1755 in   IGI   (Morpeth, Northumb); John Threlkeld, 1776, James Thirkell, 1822 in   IGI   (Kirkby Fleetham, NR Yorks).","2  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>T(h)irkill</i>,  <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>Þorkell</i>,  <i>Thorkil</i>,  <i>Thurkil</i>, a contracted form of  <i>Þorketill</i>).  Compare  Thirkettle  . If the NR Yorks family name, cited in several examples below, survived into the modern period, it will have been confused with and absorbed by (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Thirtle","meanings":["English: variant of   Thirkell   with late dissimilation of  <i>kl</i> to  <i>tl</i>."]},{"name":"Turtle","meanings":["English:","variant of   Turkel   2.","nickname from Middle English <i>turtel</i>, <i>turtle</i> ‘turtle dove’ (Old English <i>turtle</i>, <i>turtla</i>)."]},{"name":"Tuttle","meanings":["English (Norfolk, Suffolk and Berkshire):","possibly a variant of <b>Thirkell</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)irkill</i>, <i>T(h)urkill</i> (Old Norse <i>Thorkell</i>, <i>Thorkil</i>, <i>Thurkil</i>, a shortened form of <i>Thorketill</i> from the god's name <i>Thórr</i> ‘Thor’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘kettle, cauldron’).","variant of   Tuthill  ."]},{"name":"Thirkhill","meanings":["English:  see  Thirkell  ."]},{"name":"Thurtle","meanings":["English: variant of   Thirkell   with late dissimilation of  <i>kl</i> to  <i>tl</i>."]},{"name":"Turtill","meanings":["English:  see  Turtle  ."]},{"name":"Thurkle","meanings":["English:  see  Thirkell  ."]},{"name":"Thirkill","meanings":["English:  see  Thirkell  ."]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulcock  .   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes that in the parish registers of Bolton by Bowland (WR Yorks) the same family name is spelled  <i>Bulcock</i>,  <i>Bowcocke</i>, and  <i>Boocock</i> (1608–30), and that Edward Bowcock of Howgill (WR Yorks) is also called Bulcock in a will dated 1677. Compare also Alice Bowcock, 1641, Chr. Bulcock, 1646 in   IGI   (Barnoldswick, WR Yorks)."]},{"name":"Thurtell","meanings":["English: variant of   Thirkell   with late dissimilation of  <i>kl</i> to  <i>tl</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":27,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Thirkell was born about 1310, in Yorkshire, England. He married Alice Drakelowe in 1334, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1369, in England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"about 1310–1369":"umbes 1310–1369","1312–1420":"1312–1420","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1310–1369":"1310–1369","1374":"1374","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1334":"1334","1312":"1312","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1420":"1420","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1310–1369":"noin 1310–1369","1312–1420":"1312–1420","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1310–1369":"1310–1369","1374":"1374","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1334":"1334","1312":"1312","about 1325":"noin 1325","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1420":"1420","about 1310":"noin 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1310–1369":"environ 1310–1369","1312–1420":"1312–1420","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1310–1369":"1310–1369","1374":"1374","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1334":"1334","1312":"1312"